track_notes:
There is no trail to this summit and as far as I can tell, there is no easy way up.  K6HPX approached it from the West, while I decided to try it from the East.  I parked at the same spot where I would park for activating Backyard Hill W7A PE123, and walked around it on the South side to reach the Eastern flanks of Pan Quemado.  I hiked up a gully to reach the ridge, occasionally following wildlife tracks.  This is a rocky, desert bushwhack and you definitely should wear snake gaitors if you attempt it.  There are some very steep sections with some exposure.  When I went there was also evidence that this area has been used as a lookout by smugglers, both lower down as well as on the summit itself.
Note there is a 4wd dirt road between the two SOTA summits.  I do not know how to access this road but if you came in on it, you could probably cut about 2 miles of the hike out (but hardly any elevation).

The hike to Pan Quemado is a rough cactus bushwhack with a few steep sections and lots of loose rock. The summit footprint is a bit small, but should accommodate a 40m dipole or EFHW antenna. One can access the primitive road on the East side of Pan Quemado from either Manville Rd on the South, or from Avra Valley Rd on the North. Avra Valley Rd is the easier and shorter way.
track_title: Pan Quemado from the East on a Primitive Road

track_notes: This route takes the activator to the East side of Pan Quemado, just West of Backyard Hill. High ground clearance vehicle is required. Route starts at GPS 32.28991,-111.38646
track_title: Pan Quemado Drive in from Manville Rd

track_notes:
Primitive road to the summit. You will cross State Trust land so a permit will be needed.

Lots of brush along the road so expect some desert pinstripping on your vehicle.
track_title: Avra Valley Road South to Pan Quemado
